Antonio Vivaldi, also known as Vivaldi, is the Italian Baroque composer, violinist, and conductor who is now regarded as the father of violin playing and concerto performance. He composed a large variety of musical styles, including symphonies, concertos, operas, chamber music, and many sacred works, and performed them with both orchestra and solo instrument. Vivaldi also wrote one of the most popular concertos in classical music, the concertos for mandolin, violin and organ, and operas that use them, such as those from Bizet and Weber. Vivaldi is perhaps the most popular violinist of his time, which may explain why he composed so much for the instrument. His music has continued to be popular for centuries, but, with the exception of concertos in the violin's alto register and works in the piano, its music has not been recorded since the early 19th century. This is most likely because the music is not very popular, except for the most popular concertos and operas, and also because Vivaldi himself, who lived during the Enlightenment period, had few opportunities to publish his works in his lifetime.
